# Security Review: `app.js`

## Summary

The file is a minimal Express server with two GET endpoints (`/health`, `/users`). Because it has no user input, no database, and no auth layer, classic injection/authN bugs don't manifest directly — but there are several meaningful issues and a lot of missing-by-default hardening you should add before this grows.

---

## Findings

### 🔴 HIGH — A01: Broken Access Control (PII exposure on `/users`)

**Line 11-16:** `/users` returns user records including email addresses with no authentication, authorization, or rate limiting. Any unauthenticated caller can enumerate user PII.

```js
app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json([
    { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
    ...
  ]);
});
```

**Recommendation:** Require authentication and minimize the fields returned.

```js
const requireAuth = (req, res, next) => {
  const token = req.headers.authorization?.replace(/^Bearer\s+/i, '');
  if (!token || !isValidToken(token)) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Unauthorized' });
  req.user = decodeToken(token);
  next();
};

app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  // Return only non-sensitive fields by default
  res.json(users.map(({ id, name }) => ({ id, name })));
});
```

---

### 🔴 HIGH — A05: Security Misconfiguration (no security headers)

There is no `helmet()` middleware. Express also sends `X-Powered-By: Express` by default, which aids fingerprinting.

**Recommendation:**

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.disable('x-powered-by');
app.use(helmet());
app.use(helmet.hsts({ maxAge: 31536000, includeSubDomains: true, preload: true }));
```

---

### 🟠 MEDIUM — A04: Insecure Design (no rate limiting)

Both endpoints can be hit unbounded, enabling enumeration and trivial DoS.

**Recommendation:**

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 60, standardHeaders: true, legacyHeaders: false }));
```

---

### 🟠 MEDIUM — A05: Missing CORS policy

No explicit CORS configuration — behavior depends on downstream proxies. If this is an API consumed by a known origin, pin it explicitly; if it's internal, block cross-origin.

```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({ origin: ['https://app.example.com'], methods: ['GET'], credentials: false }));
```

---

### 🟠 MEDIUM — A09: No logging or error handling

There is no request logging, no global error handler, and no 404 handler. Unhandled errors will leak stack traces to clients in default Express behavior.

```js
